src/backend/parser/README.key_join

FOR KEY Joins
=============

This file gives a short overview of how FOR KEY joins work, followed by a
glossary of the vocabulary used by the implementation.  The code lives
mainly in parse_key_join.c, with the supporting node types in
nodes/parsenodes.h.

Overview
--------

A FOR KEY clause declares that one join input references another through a
foreign key, so each referencing row is matched to its single referenced
row.  In the raw parse tree it is a JoinExpr whose keyJoin field holds a
KeyJoinClause.

transformAndValidateKeyJoin() (parse_key_join.c) handles it, called from the
JoinExpr transformation in parse_clause.c alongside the ON and USING qual
handlers, once both operands are transformed and their namespaces are
available.  It:

  1. Resolves the named columns against each operand's surface, gathers facts
     about those surfaces from the catalog (foreign-key, unique, and not-null
     constraints), and propagates them up the query, deactivating any that
     a step invalidates.
  2. Proves three things over the named columns: the referenced key values
     are unique, every non-null referencing value is contained in them, and
     referencing nulls cannot silently drop rows.  A failed proof rejects the
     query here.
  3. Generates the equality quals into JoinExpr.quals and replaces the raw
     KeyJoinClause on JoinExpr.keyJoin with a KeyJoinNode identifying the
     proof's referencing and referenced sides and columns.

The clause is not rewritten away: the join executes as an ordinary equijoin
through the generated quals, while the retained KeyJoinNode records the
proof.

The relationship
----------------

referencing / referenced
    The two sides of the relationship.  The referencing side holds the
    foreign-key columns; the referenced side holds the unique columns they
    point at.  The arrow direction in FOR KEY chooses which input is which.

usable (key)
    A constraint sound enough to ground a proof: a foreign key that is
    enforced, validated, and non-deferrable, or a unique/primary key with
    the matching properties.  Constraints that are NOT VALID or deferrable
    are not usable.

key identity
    The (type, typmod, collation, equality operator) signature that a
    referencing position and its referenced position must share for the
    generated equality to be valid.

key position (KeyJoinKeyPosition)
    One column-component of a (possibly composite) key, together with the
    surface type it exposes and the equality operator used at that position.

containment
    The property that every all-non-null referencing key value appears among
    the referenced key values -- one of the conditions a proof establishes.

Proving a key join
------------------

proof
    The parse-time derivation that a key join is sound: referenced
    uniqueness, containment of referencing values, and correct handling of
    nulls.

fact (KeyJoinFact)
    One transient piece of evidence used while building a proof.  Four
    kinds: unique, foreign-key, row-coverage, and not-null.

surface
    The set of columns a range-table entry exposes to the query level above
    it.  "Surface facts" are the facts attached to that exposed set; they are
    cached per RTE and computed on demand.

row coverage (KJF_ROW_COVERAGE)
    Evidence that every all-non-null referenced key value still reaches a
    given point -- that is, needed referenced rows have not been filtered
    away by a clause below.

active / inactive fact
    Whether a fact survived propagation.  An invalidated fact is not dropped
    but kept inactive, stamped with a KeyJoinInactiveReason, so a later
    rejection can explain why a needed fact was lost.

propagation
    Carrying facts upward through joins, grouping, and projection, marking
    inactive any fact that a step invalidates (for example, DISTINCT or an
    outer join can end row coverage).

base-table vs derived proof
    A proof grounded directly in base-table constraints, versus one carried
    through views, subqueries, CTEs, or earlier key joins whose definitions
    keep the needed facts visible.
